<body>

<header class="hero">
  <div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">Materials Science &middot; ENGR 170</p>
    <h1>Seeing the physics behind the properties</h1>
    <p class="lede">A set of browser-based animations I built for teaching materials science. Each one takes a quantitative result &mdash; a melting point, a modulus, a diffraction condition &mdash; and makes it something you can drag, rotate, and reason through, rather than take on faith.</p>
    <p class="byline">Deborah Glosser &middot; <a href="https://engineeringdesign.wwu.edu/people/glosser">Western Washington University</a></p>
  </div>
</header>

<main class="wrap">

  <section id="bonding" aria-labelledby="bonding-h">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-tag t-bond">Interatomic bonding</span>
    </div>
    <h2 id="bonding-h">From a single potential well to a table of properties</h2>
    <div class="sec-rule"></div>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">01</span>
          <span class="chip">U(r) &middot; Morse potential</span>
        </div>
        <h3>The interatomic potential well</h3>
        <p class="desc">Drag the well's depth, spacing, and curvature and watch one interatomic potential set three macroscopic properties at once: bond energy &rarr; melting temperature, equilibrium separation &rarr; atomic size, and curvature at the bottom &rarr; elastic modulus.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="potential-well.html" loading="lazy" title="Interactive interatomic potential well U(r)"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="potential-well.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">02</span>
          <span class="chip">ionic &middot; covalent &middot; metallic</span>
        </div>
        <h3>Same shear, opposite outcomes</h3>
        <p class="desc">Apply the same shear to ionic, covalent, and metallic bonds and get cleavage, brittle fracture, or ductile slip &mdash; a demonstration that bonding <em>character</em>, not just bond strength, decides how a material fails.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="shear-outcomes.html" loading="lazy" title="Same shear applied to ionic, covalent, and metallic bonds"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="shear-outcomes.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">03</span>
          <span class="chip">property table, derived</span>
        </div>
        <h3>One bonding physics, four readouts</h3>
        <p class="desc">A synthesis figure: melting point, stiffness, conductivity, and ductility all trace back to just two roots &mdash; the shape of the energy well and the behavior of the electrons. The property table stops being a list to memorize and becomes something derived.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="property-table.html" loading="lazy" title="The property table derived from bonding physics"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="property-table.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section id="crystal" aria-labelledby="crystal-h">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <span class="sec-tag t-cryst">Crystal structure &amp; diffraction</span>
    </div>
    <h2 id="crystal-h">Lattices, the geometry within them, and how we measure them</h2>
    <div class="sec-rule"></div>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">04</span>
          <span class="chip">FCC &middot; BCC &middot; HCP</span>
        </div>
        <h3>Crystal structures of metals</h3>
        <p class="desc">FCC, BCC, and HCP unit cells you can rotate and inflate to their touching radius, with live atom counts and atomic packing factors updating as you go.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="crystal-structures.html" loading="lazy" title="FCC, BCC, and HCP crystal structures"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="crystal-structures.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">05</span>
          <span class="chip">a&ndash;R geometry</span>
        </div>
        <h3>Deriving the a&ndash;R relation</h3>
        <p class="desc">Where <em>a</em> = 2&radic;2&thinsp;R &mdash; and its BCC and HCP cousins &mdash; actually comes from: the geometry of atoms touching along the close-packed direction, built up one step at a time instead of handed over as a formula.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="a-R-relation.html" loading="lazy" title="Deriving the a-R relation for FCC, BCC, HCP"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="a-R-relation.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>

    <article class="card">
      <div class="card-head">
        <div class="card-top">
          <span class="num">06</span>
          <span class="chip">2d&middot;sin&theta; = n&lambda;</span>
        </div>
        <h3>Bragg's law, from scratch</h3>
        <p class="desc">Where 2d&middot;sin&theta; comes from: the extra path length between rays reflecting off adjacent lattice planes, shown as the interference condition that turns a diffraction pattern into a measurement of spacing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="frame"><iframe src="bragg-law.html" loading="lazy" title="Derivation of Bragg's law"></iframe></div>
      <div class="card-foot"><a class="open" href="bragg-law.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Open full &nearr;</a></div>
    </article>
  </section>

</main>

<footer>
  <div class="wrap foot-grid">
    <p class="foot-note">Built as teaching tools for ENGR 170, Introduction to Materials Science &amp; Engineering. Each animation runs entirely in the browser &mdash; no install, no plugins.</p>
    <p class="foot-meta">Deborah Glosser &middot; WWU</p>
  </div>
</footer>

